title: For Sale:  All Matching Swiss Vetterli M78 A BEAUTY! + Rod 13 Shot Repeater
postcontent:
This listing is for one of the lowest priced and finest looking Vetterli M78s I have seen in a long while. For those new to this rifle, these fire a .41 rimfire round that is all but impossible to find. So right up front, you will likely not be shooting this one unless you get lucky and find 1 or 2 rounds as they are sold that way (and for a LOT). If you know what this rifle is though, you probably already know a lot about it and realize its collector appeal. Many owners have converted the rifle to fire a centerfire version of the cartridge that you can reload BUT it involves permanent changes to the bolt so many used extra bolts. This means that a pretty rare rifle has become even rarer in original condition as many have been "ruined" in this way, and extra bolts sell for a LOT of money and are all but impossible to find. In fact, this rifle is listed for just twice what an original bolt can sell for, and you get the rest of the rifle too! Here is a little info on the rimfire design and round--*** Although a rimfire round, it shot further and flatter than most of it's contemporaries. The Vetterli striker has a forked firing pin which passes through two firing pins holes in the bolt face for a double strike on the rimfire cartridge, improving the likelihood of ignition*** 
The basics are------ Weight: 10.1 lbs empty Chambering: 10.4x38 (.41) Swiss Rimfire Rifling: 4 groove, RH twist, 1 in 26" Velocity: 1425 fps Capacity: 13 (12 round tube magazine +1 in the cartridge elevator)
 Total Production: 15,770 Manufacture Dates: 1878-1881 Eidgenössische Waffenfabrik, Bern.
 In the 1880s, 15,000 or so were made and in the last 130 years, many have been lost to time, corrosion, fire and hundreds (or perhaps thousands including private collections)reside in museums and permanent collections around the world. Out of the remainders, 1000s have been converted to centerfire meaning there are just a few thousand of nicer unconverted M78 rifles left, with not all of them in the USA. Many who collect no-FFL antique rifles, or Swiss rifles, or repeating rifles from this era desire a fine condition Vetterli M78 as it is the ultimate design and firepower from the era. There is a long tube magazine in the front wood which is similar to other designs of the time (My Kropatschek I will be listing is another) and gave this rifle a rate of fire of over 20 rounds per minute in trained hands. With 13 rounds on hand, that is serious firepower for the 1880s.
 The details for THIS rifle are- All matching numbers, including the little pieces which is typical for these as the Swiss never used these in any war. ** The underside of the barrel has a 35 and another 4 digit number but these are not the serial number which is on the top..those are other codes that you can look up online**The metal finish has a mottled patina and I did not attempt to rub or clean it.  It is very good overall and as I got this as a part of a trade and do not collect rifles that they do not sell ammo or brass for, I am selling it exactly as I received it. That is pretty fine looking on the exterior. The wood is superb for these and is free from cracks and splits. I did remove the front wood piece to check the numbers and markings (in the photos) and as usual, the metal finish underneath is far superior to the exposed areas which are pretty nice too. The barrel does not have the same mottling and is a pretty even and dark original finish. The rifle functions perfect with the bolt retracted, it pops the elevator and lifter up carrying another round from the tube magazine. No internal rust or corrosion on the mechanism which would really not even need a cleaning as it is pretty darn exceptional. The DOWN SIDE, and there has to be one or I would list this at $450 and still be lower than many others. This fired a black powder round and the inside of the bore looks crudded. I am not going to attempt cleaning, rather sell it as I received it for a couple hundred less. As I will not be keeping this for my collection, I don't want to spend time on it, just pass it along. It may clean up nice or may require heavy scrubbing and still be fair or poor, I do not know BUT!! as the chances of this being fired are quite slim, it may not matter to a collector as a fully functioning and nice condition Vetterli may be what is important. If you are planning to convert this to centerfire, it may not be worth the effort, besides the fact that you would need another bolt or have to ruin the value of this one. So check the photos, ask any questions and I priced it well below any other to make up for the bore needing attention, which may not even matter to many buyers. Ships direct to you for $38 as it is long and heavy. 36 inches long packed and probably a bit over 11 pounds, and don't forget that Fedex adds $4 to deliver to a residence. If you have a business address and it does not cost $4 I will deduct $4 from the shipping. Also, if you are closer and the shipping is significantly less, I will also refund the extra. Paypal add $5 as we will split the fees. ***I have MANY more photos, so if interested, ask and I weill send you 10 or so other photos that show every angle and part

postcontent: Sale Pending upon receiving confirmation from Ruger for being one of about 30 with it's rare variation. This is another RARE Revolver from our Dad's estate and looks to be New in the Box as you can see by it's finish. It is one of Ruger's Recall guns that were put out in 1993/94 and came with BOTH 22LR (.223) and 22Mag (.224) Cylinder's from the Ruger Factory as you can see by the Conformation letter from Ruger. These had special barrels also as the bores were .224 to accommodate the 22 Mag Ammo instead of the standard .223 for 22LR. We also have a recall letter that came from Ruger letting the people that bought them know that they were being recalled. From what the estate was told there were under a 1000 built but most were sent back to Ruger with there 22Mag cylinders and then Ruger sent back the guns WITHOUT the 22Mag cylinders. Story being the timing may be off too far for the 22MAG cylinder and might raise the cup pressure over the maximum limit. The firearm absolutely has to be transferred to you and the paper work done as I Prefer to sell FTF at an FFL only. title: For Sale:  1944 German Mauser k98 rare AR marked late war model
location: Moncks Corner Goose Creek, Charleston, South Carolina
postcontent: This is a very nice example of a late war k98 Mauser in 8mm (7.92) 90% numbers matching. Very clean and bright bore, little to no wear at the crown. about a quarter inch between the crown and the casing when checking with a live round. Has a great Petina. The swastika's have been peened and the barrel is import marked. Don't think it was Russian capture gun, in fact I can't figure out who captured it. Receiver is marked AR 44 on the top. Which is the Mauser Borsigwalde factory in Berlin. Serial number is 3930*. Absolutely no rust of any kind, most of the bluing is still there and in nice shape, especially under the wood. The bolt is the only number that doesn't match, but it looks to be original. I'm no K98 expert, but all the internet commando's out there seem to know everything, and I'm tired of reading all the blogs. The front sight hood is not correct, but it's been on the rifle for a long time. Original hoods are easy to find. This was made just before the Kreigsmodel (late war versions that they cut corners on to save time and money) but it does have some of the features, like no locking screws on the trigger plate, no numbers anywhere on the rear sight. The follower is marked 135, or at least I think that's what is says. The serial number is on: The receiver Both Barrel bands Both pieces of the stock, upper and lower and it's only visible on the inside. The stock has no external markings that I can find. I based my price off of k98's that have actually sold recently on other sites. I left some meat on the bone (priced it lower than the comps I referenced) Not really looking for trades, need the $$ to take care of some flood issues. I have several photo's on my phone that I can text or maybe email to you. But like anything old and expensive, it's better to hold it in your hands so you can make a better decision. Just my 2 cents. Call or text is best. My response time on emails is pretty slow and my spam filter is very aggressive. 843 six seven zero 9636
